Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels - For most of the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in countering powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at zero levels while conducting multiple unprecedented expansions of its balance sheet through large-scale bond purchasing operations.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank also followed the Federal Reserve's lead, each implementing their own versions of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But inflation has not seen a reasonable increase anywhere.
Although these countries are all battling deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — and economic performance — are diverging.
The growth in the U.S. and the U.K. is now strong enough to allow them to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the eurozone and Japan are increasing their QE measures, pushing long-term policy interest rates further into negative territory.
What is the reason for this difference?
The short answer is debt.
For many years, the United States and the United Kingdom have consistently run current account deficits, making them debtor countries, while the Eurozone and Japan have maintained external surpluses, making them creditor countries.
Negative interest rates benefit debt countries but harm creditor countries. Therefore, the negative interest rates introduced after the global economic crisis stimulated recovery in the United States and the United Kingdom, but had little effect on the Eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, most creditor countries in the world—nations with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland—have experienced negative interest rates, not only on long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also on medium-term bonds.
This is certainly not a good thing.
Despite the limited effectiveness of low interest rates, the central banks of these economies continue to adhere to this policy.
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot bring benefits to the economy, they will change the subject and counter the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — an argument that appears flawless on the surface.
But in reality, it's full of loopholes.
Basic economics courses mention the peculiar phenomenon of the "backward-bending savings supply curve": in certain circumstances, a decrease in interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because falling interest rates reduce the income of savers, they will cut back on spending, especially if they have a goal of saving for retirement.
None of this is meant to negate the general rule — which forms the basis of modern monetary policy — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other forms of spending.
However, the impact varies due to differences in the debt situations of the economies.
In a closed economy, every creditor has a debtor, so whatever the creditor loses due to extremely low interest rates, the debtor should benefit.
However, in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors naturally outnumber debtors.
The situation is exactly the opposite for a country with a large amount of foreign debt.
Therefore, the effects of monetary policy with a lower bound on interest rates differ between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important because foreign asset positions were often small (as a percentage of GDP).
However, today, the foreign asset positions of major industrialized economies are substantial and increasingly diversified, partly due to the leverage that contributed to the 2007-2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, at the national level, leverage is still continuing to increase.
Although the overall current account imbalances have eased since the beginning of the financial crisis, they have not reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to reinforce their status as creditors, diverging from deficit economies.
Some major commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have experienced significant current account surpluses when oil prices are high, making them the main exceptions to the diversification of foreign asset holdings.
Since June 2014, the world oil price has plummeted, causing a reversal in the wealth trends of these countries.
Their export revenues sharply declined — many countries losing half — forcing them into deficits, relying on their large sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodities boom.
Nowadays, a significant reduction in spending has become inevitable.
Industrialized economies face completely different challenges.
Their problem — in a sense, a luxury problem — is to ensure that consumers spend the windfall they gain from the drop in import prices.
However, in creditor countries, negative interest rates do not seem to be advancing this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence also exists within the Eurozone.
Although the Eurozone as a whole is a creditor economy, it also includes debtor countries within it.
Debt-based economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debts.
But the current account surpluses of traditional debt countries are too large, leading to a continued increase in the asymmetry between debt and creditor countries.
Most noteworthy is that since the outbreak of the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that the surplus accumulated during this period exceeded the total historical surplus prior to this.
According to the current trend, Germany's net foreign asset position may increase from 60% to 100% of GDP.
The central bank governor should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to have little patience, struggling greatly with low inflation, despite the output gap gradually closing and both the U.S. and Japan achieving full employment.
Central bank governors of debtor nations must stop manipulating their economies with additional monetary easing that may be detrimental to production.
On the contrary, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of the declining oil prices to disappear.
ECB President Draghi recently acknowledged that the current monetary policy framework may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more of the same is not a solution.
